<section id="forms-introduction" class="introduction">

	<header class="container">

		<h2>Forms</h2>

		<p>Forms in watercolor are pretty simple, yet tremendously flexible. Forms consist of a <code>form</code> tag containing <code>label</code>, <code>input</code>, and <code>button</code> elements. To keep things consistent and flexible each form field should be enclosed in a <code>div</code> with a <code>field</code> class. The form buttons should be enclosed in a <code>div</code> with a <code>buttons</code> class.  With that consistent code structure you can organize your form in a consistent manner that best fits the form content with a few simple classes that you can put on the <code>form</code> or on the field containers.</p>

	</header>

</section>

<section id="forms" class="container">

	<article id="form-types">

		<h3>Form Types</h3>
		<p>There are three basic form types: <code>block</code>, <code>inline</code>, or <code>align</code>. Each type of form you wish to use can be implemented, with the same markup, by simply adding the corresponding class to the <code>form</code> element, <code>fieldset</code> element, or at a field level on the field's containing <code>div</code> element.</p>
		<p>To get started here is an example of a basic Watercolor form. This shows the basic structure of markup needed to work with the classes provided for styling the various form types. This example shows that each form field is enclosed in a <code>div</code> element with <code>field</code> class, and the form buttons are also enclosed in a <code>div</code> element with <code>buttons</code> class.</p>

		<table class="bordered">

			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th style="width: 25%">form type</th>
					<th>description</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>

			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td><code>block</code></td>
					<td>Each form field is displayed on a separate line, with the label above the field. This is the default form type if no class is specified.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><code>inline</code></td>
					<td>Each form field is displayed in an inline manner, with the label above the field.  The buttons are displayed below the form on a separate line.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><code>align</code></td>
					<td>Each form field is displayed on a separate line, with the field labels aligned to the left of the field.  The buttons are displayed below the form on a separate line.</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>

		</table>

	</article>

	<article id="block-form">

		<h3>Block Form</h3>
		<p>Block form type is the default form type in Watercolor if no form type class is provided. This format displays each field on a separate line, with labels above the field.  The buttons are displayed below the form on a separate line. To use this form type add class <code>block</code> to the <code>form</code>, <code>fieldset</code>, or directly on a field container.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<form>

				<div class="field">
					<label>First Name:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="field">
					<label>Last Name:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="Last Name" value="" />
				</div>
				
				<div class="field">
					<label>Email:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="user@domain.com" required />
					<span class="hint">Email address is required and must be in the format: user@@domain.com</span>
				</div>

				<div class="buttons">
					<input type="submit" class="fb-button primary" /> <input type="reset" class="fb-button" value="Reset" />
				</div>

			</form>

		</div>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;form class="block"&gt;
   &lt;div class="field"&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;First Name&lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" /&gt;
   &lt;/div&gt;
   &lt;div class="field"&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;Last Name&lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;input type="text" placeholder="Last Name" value="" /&gt;
   &lt;/div&gt;
   &lt;div class="field"&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;Email&lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;input type="text" placeholder="user@domain.com" required /&gt;
      &lt;span class="hint"&gt;Email address is required and must be in the format: user@@domain.com&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;/div&gt;
   &lt;div class="buttons"&gt;
      &lt;input type="submit" class="fb-button primary" /&gt;
      &lt;input type="reset" class="fb-button" value="Reset" /&gt;
   &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>

	</article>

	<article id="inline-form">

		<h3>Inline Form</h3>
		<p>Inline format displays each field side-by-side on one line, with labels above the field.  To move a field to the next line add a <code>clear</code> class to the field container &mdash; more on this <a href="#clear-form">below</a>. The buttons are displayed below the form on a separate line. To use this form type add class <code>inline</code> to the <code>form</code>, <code>fieldset</code>, or directly on a field container.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<form class="inline">

				<div class="field">
					<label>First Name:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="field">
					<label>Last Name:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="Last Name" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="buttons">
					<input type="submit" class="fb-button primary" /> <input type="reset" class="fb-button" value="Reset" />
				</div>

			</form>

		</div>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;form class="inline"&gt;
   &lt;div class="field"&gt;
