	<article id="hybrid-form">

		<h3>Field Format Overrides</h3>
		<p>Add class <code>block</code>, <code>inline</code>, or <code>align</code> to any field to override the specified parent form style. In this example we have an aligned form in which the "Email" and "Email (confirm)" fields are overridden with <code>inline</code> format, while the "Comments" field is overridden with <code>block</code> format. In most cases you wouldn't need to do something like this, but if you need to this is how it is done.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<form class="align">

				<div class="field">
					<label>First Name:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="field">
					<label>Last Name:</label>
					<input type="text" placeholder="Last Name" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="field">
					<label>Gender:</label>
					<select>
						<option>Male</option>
						<option>Female</option>
					</select>
				</div>

				<div class="field inline">
					<label>Email:</label>
					<input type="email" placeholder="user@domain.com" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="field inline">
					<label>Email (confirm):</label>
					<input type="email" placeholder="user@domain.com" value="" />
				</div>

				<div class="field block">
					<label>Comments:</label>
					<textarea placeholder="Comments"></textarea>
				</div>
				
				<div class="buttons">
					<input type="submit" class="fb-button primary" /> <input type="reset" class="fb-button" value="Reset" />
				</div>

			</form>

		</div>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;form class="align"&gt;
   &lt;div class="field"&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;First Name&lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" /&gt;
   &lt;/div&gt;
   &lt;div class="field"&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;Last Name&lt;/label&gt;
