	<article id="fieldsets">

		<h3>Fieldsets</h3>
		<p>When using fieldsets you have two options: you can place the class <code>block</code>, <code>inline</code>, or <code>align</code> on the form, or you can place the class on each fieldset and omit it from the form. If you place a class on both it could cause unintended behaviors.  Overriding at a field level works just fine in any case.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<form>

				<fieldset class="align">
					<legend>Basic Information</legend>

					<div class="field">
						<label>First Name:</label>
						<input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" />
					</div>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Last Name:</label>
						<input type="text" placeholder="Last Name" value="" />
					</div>
					
					<div class="field">
						<label>Gender:</label>
						<select>
							<option value="1">Male</option>
							<option value="2">Female</option>
						</select>
					</div>

				</fieldset>

				<fieldset class="inline">
					<legend>Contact Information</legend>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Email:</label>
						<input type="email" placeholder="user@domain.com" value="" />
					</div>
				
					<div class="field">
						<label>Email (confirm):</label>
						<input type="email" placeholder="user@domain.com" value="" />
					</div>

				</fieldset>

				<fieldset class="block">
					<legend>Additional Information</legend>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Comments:</label>
						<textarea>Comments</textarea>
					</div>

				</fieldset>
				
				<div class="buttons">
					<input type="submit" class="fb-button primary" /> <input type="reset" class="fb-button" value="Reset" />
				</div>

			</form>

		</div>

